ce:section.ce:para:
Both Nyquist impedance plots (Fig. 8
                           ) and the equivalent circuit model (Fig. 9
                           ) can provide insights into the corrosion behavior and the effectiveness of PP coated steel via various concentrations of DCQDs in 1.0 M-HCl. It is evident that the characteristic feature of the impedance response is semicircles, indicating a capacitive type behavior. The size of these semicircles was increased versus the DCQDs concentration up to 400 mg/L. Fig. 9 represents an equivalent circuit model used for analyzing the impedance spectra and the computer fitting of the measured data for Nyquist plot for PPC coated steel contain 400 mg/L DCQDs in 1.0 M-HCl solution. The equivalent circuit model we used was based on previously published work, including our recent study [45] and other authors' works [46,47]. The model has been effective in analyzing similar impedance diagrams. Fitting the EIS data to the equivalent circuit model revealed a good agreement between the fitted and measured spectra. The repeatability of all measurements was ±0.001 to ±0.18 and error less than 1%. The Rct value is crucial for measurement of electron transfer through the metal surface and was inversely proportional to the rate of corrosion. The activation control of dissolution process accounts that the rate of corrosion was influenced by the reaction activation energy, providing insights into the reaction kinetics of the corrosion. The observed changes in the size of capacitive semicircles versus various concentrations of DCQDs point out to the resistance increase of the PP coat against corrosion by 1.0 M-HCl.
